{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b57cba97-32ff-4899-9a85-d573f46325f3","content":"**The scope lifetime is different in MAUI vs ASP.NET Core.**\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates one instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a natural scope boundary. In MAUI, there's no request pipeline, so the default scope is the **entire application lifetime**. This means `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your `DbContext` is reused across all page navigations, accumulating tracked entities.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — gives a fresh instance each time it's injected.\n\n2. **Create explicit scopes** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Manually reset tracking** if you keep scoped registration:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the simplest. Option 2 gives you precise control over the `DbContext` lifetime, similar to per-request behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1ff4eac-d045-44ce-9756-bd3a83ec753f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question — no code to look at, no repo to explore. I can answer directly.\n\nThe core issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no HTTP request pipeline — the default DI container has a single scope for the entire app lifetime. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app session, causing stale/persisted data across navigations.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"7FC4:11463F:60E8B24:69CB7A3:69F1591A"},"id":"f77f2abf-ce07-4bf1-a21e-4f86c5002dd7","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:04:36.343Z","parentId":"db7ac586-9032-4b06-af45-2ce3e2842613"}
